model_explanation: the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave grapes to no one else. S2 states that Sam didn’t give grapes to Tom, which aligns with the idea that only Ellen received grapes. Thus, S2 is entailed by S1.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave apples to no one else. However, S2 says Sam didn’t give Ellen apples, which directly contradicts the assertion in S1 that Ellen did receive apples.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning that Sam gave grapes to Rob and no one else. S2, by saying Sam also gave Ellen grapes, contradicts this. Therefore, it is contradicted.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning that Sam gave apples to only Rob and no one else. S2 says Sam also gave Ellen apples, which contradicts the claim in S1. Therefore, it is contradicted.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave apples to no one else. S2 states that Sam didn’t give Bill apples, which aligns perfectly with the claim in S1. Therefore, it is entailed.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning Sam gave apples to no one else. S2’s claim that Sam didn’t give Sue apples follows directly from that idea. Therefore, it is entailed.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning Sam gave oranges to Rob and no one else (with respect to oranges). S2, however, speaks about apples, which is a different category and doesn’t contradict or follow from S1. The two statements are independent.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning Sam gave apples to Rob and no one else (with respect to apples). S2 talks about grapes, which is a different item altogether. Hence, they are independent.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on "ROB," meaning Sam gave bananas to Rob and no one else. S2’s statement that Sam didn’t give Ellen bananas naturally follows from that. Therefore, it is entailed.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on "MARY," meaning Sam gave apples to Mary and no one else. S2 says that Sam also gave Ellen apples, which contradicts the exclusivity described in S1. Therefore, it is contradicted.
